sub_title: Crocs Benelux Representative | Pioneer sales developer for SMEs & large enterprises | Polyglot information retriever | Intercultural business consultant
summary:
I work very well in multicultural environments and I am polyglot.
There are three areas within the work arena that I am passionate about and that I am vehemently involved in: improving internal processes in companies, connecting all kinds of people and creating creative low-cost solutions. Let me explain a bit about each: 

when I see that something is not working well due to a lack of interaction between teams, I tend to be the connector that leads to cooperation and product improvement. This has happened very recently at Crocs where we have been working for a long time in sales with order forms and catalogues that I noticed were not ideal for the customer. In the case of the order form, by contacting the person who made it, I proposed a new model that turned out to be much more effective and is now used in all direct markets in Europe. The same happened with the catalogue, for which I proposed a new design that was consulted with other sales representatives and redesigned the order and categories of the products. From 2023 onwards we will have a new catalogue design.

As I am passionate about connecting different people, I started in 2017 a non-governmental organization that worked with refugees in the Netherlands to facilitate their access to employment. Together with them I designed a project that won a prize and a subsidy from the King and Queen of the Netherlands. It was carried out together with local universities.

And creative solutions, that's something innate in me. Recently I helped in a simple way to improve the labelling of shipments to customers, reducing the error in the logistics system, shipping costs and returns. 

I'm always interested in hearing from those who are interested in these issues and of course those who need my help. If you are interested in my services, please do not hesitate to contact me via LinkedIn messages.
